Install

install_github('devtools')
library('devtools')
install_github('chipMap','xons')
library('chipMap')

Get start

We need a bed file of peak regions, can be a result from a ChIPseq peak calling. For example, a bed file peak_example.bed.

peak=bed2gr('peak_example.bed')

Annotate the peak

The heatmap can be made without this step. Here we will do further annotation before making heatmaps.

ann=annPeak(peak,tx) ##annotate the peaks with nearest transcripts/genes
ann_tss=annPeak_bytss(peak,tx)## annotate the peaks with nearest TSS

Heatmap

We need BigWig files for making the heatmap. Here is an example using peak_example.bw and H3K4me3_example.bw.

fls=c('peak_example.bw','H3K4me3_example.bw')
bwls=lapply(fls,bw2coverage)
names(bwls)=fls

Centered at TSS

Use tssMap function to make heatmaps centered at TSS. It can be done with any given TSS with the columns requested by tssMap function. Here we centered at the nearest gene of peaks as an example and make a heatmap of H3K4me3.

## Filter to keep unique TSS that overlapping with peaks and sort the TSS by the occupancy of H3K4me3.
ann_tss_sub=subset(ann_tss,distance==0) ## get TSS with peak
ann_tss_uq=ann_tss_sub[!duplicated(ann_tss_sub$txid),] ## get unique TSS
## Calculate the matrix
query=bwls[[2]]
mx=tssMap(query,anndf=ann_tss_uq) #Default is -5 kb to 5 kb around TSS.
ord=order(rowSums(mx),decreasing=T)
mx.sort=mx[ord,] #sort the TSS by the occupancy of H3K4me3
## Plot the heatmap
plotMX(list(peak_example=mx.sort),output="heatmap_peak.pdf")
## png 
##   2

A PDF version of the heatmap and colorbar are saved to allow text editing, like this:


We can make heatmap of multiple samples. Here we just show two samples, it can be much more.

ann_tss_uq_sort=ann_tss_uq[ord,] #sort the TSS by the occupancy of H3K4me3
mxls=lapply(bwls,tssMap,anndf=ann_tss_uq_sort) # This step can be paralleled using mclapply.
plotMX(mxls,output="heatmap.tss.center.pdf")
## png 
##   2

A PDF version of the heatmap and colorbar are saved to allow text editing, like this:


We can make the meta plot, the mean of each column, to give a summary profile of the matrix.

metaPlot(mxls, titles="tss.center", center="tss") ## image is autosaved as PNG. PDF can be saved if out.pdf=TRUE.
## png 
##   2

Centered at peak center

Use peakMap to center the heatmap at the middle of the peak. Here we use annotated peak data frame as an example. It can be any given peak regions with the columns requested by peakMap function.

## Calculate the matrix, sort the peak by the peak width.
mxls.peak=lapply(bwls,peakMap,anndf=ann_tss,sortByWidth=TRUE) #Default is -5 kb to 5 kb around peak center.
## Plot the heatmap
plotMX(mxls.peak,output="heatmap.peak.center.pdf") 
## png 
##   2
## metaPlot
metaPlot(mxls.peak, titles="peak.center", center="peak")
## png 
##   2

A PDF version of the heatmap and colorbar are saved to allow text editing, like this:


We can sort the peak by the distance of peak center to its nearest TSS.

## sort the peak by distance_center_to_tss.
ann_tss_sort_dis=ann_tss[order(ann_tss$distance_center_to_tss),] 
## Calculate the matrix of -5 kb to 5 kb around peak center.
mxls.peak.dis=lapply(bwls,peakMap,anndf=ann_tss_sort_dis, left= -5000, right=5000, bin_width=25)
## Plot the heatmap
plotMX(mxls.peak.dis,output="heatmap.peak.center.dis.pdf") 
## png 
##   2

A PDF version of the heatmap and colorbar are saved to allow text editing, like this:


Tip: The peaks can be separated into groups by overlapping TSS or not and make heatmap separately. Just split the annotated peak data frame ann or ann_tss into groups based on peak_to_feature or distance column.

Enrichment profile

Instead of heatmap, we can plot enrichment profile, which is binary profile of peak binding. It shows whether there is a peak or not at certain location. It contrasts from the background input by peak calling, so it is much cleaner than the heatmap.

Instead of BigWig files, we just need Bed files to make the enrichment profile.

Centered at TSS

h3k4me3=bed2gr('H3K4me3_peak.bed')
pls=list(peak_example=peak,H3K4me3=h3k4me3) ## a list of GRanges

mxls.enrich=lapply(pls,tssMap,anndf=ann_tss_uq_sort)
plotMX(mxls.enrich,output="enrich.tss.center.pdf",color=c("white","purple"))
## png 
##   2
metaPlot(mxls.enrich, titles="enrich.tss.center", center="tss")
## png 
##   2

PDF output enrichment profile is saved (the colorbar is useless here), like this:

Centered at peak center

## Calculate the matrix
mxls.peak.enrich=lapply(pls,peakMap,anndf=ann_tss,sortByWidth=TRUE) #Default is -5 kb to 5 kb around peak center.
## Plot the enrichment profile
plotMX(mxls.peak.enrich,output="enrich.peak.center.pdf",color=c("white","purple")) 
## png 
##   2
## metaPlot
metaPlot(mxls.peak.enrich, "enrich.peak.center", center="peak")
## png 
##   2

PDF output enrichment profile is saved, like this:

We can sort the peak by the distance of peak center to its nearest TSS.

## Calculate the matrix of -5 kb to 5 kb around peak center.
mxls.peak.dis.enrich=lapply(pls,peakMap,anndf=ann_tss_sort_dis)
## Plot the enrichment profile
plotMX(mxls.peak.dis.enrich,output="enrich.peak.center.dis.pdf",color=c("white","purple")) 
## png 
##   2

PDF output enrichment profile is saved, like this:
